{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "The apparent cure had raised the thrilling possibility that aggressive early treatment might be able to reverse infections in newborns \u2014 and perhaps even in newly infected adults.", "abstract": "National Institutes of Health reports child in Mississippi who was thought to have been cured of HIV with aggressive drug treatment immediately after birth is now showing signs of infection with virus; findings are serious setback to hopes for cure for AIDS; about 2.3 million people worldwide were newly infected with HIV in 2012, with 260,000 infants infected at birth or immediately afterward.", "section_name": "Health", "print_page": "1", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"lastname": "McNEIL", "qualifier": "Jr", "rank": 1, "firstname": "Donald", "role": "reported", "organization": "", "middlename": "G."}], "original": "By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr", "contributor": ""}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/11/health/signs-of-infection-seen-in-child-believed-to-have-been-cured-of-hiv.html", "lead_paragraph": "The apparent cure had raised the thrilling possibility that aggressive early treatment might be able to reverse infections in newborns \u2014 and perhaps even in newly infected adults.", "headline": {"main": "Evidence of H.I.V. Found in a Child Said to Be Cured", "print_headline": "Evidence of H.I.V. Found in a Child Said to Be Cured"}, "_id": "53befe3738f0d85829e27806", "word_count": "916", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2014/07/11/us/JP-HIV1/JP-HIV1-thumbWide.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2014/07/11/us/JP-HIV1/JP-HIV1-thumbWide.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 800, "url": "images/2014/07/11/us/JP-HIV1/JP-HIV1-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2014/07/11/us/JP-HIV1/JP-HIV1-articleLarge.jpg", "xlargewidth": "600", "xlargeheight": "800"}, "subtype": "xlarge", "width": 600, "type": "image"}, {"height": 75